Plants of the genus
Bersama
( Melianthaceae family) are broadly dispersed in sub-Saharan Africa (
).
Bersama abyssinica (Fresen)
Melianthaceae is widely distributed in Kenya . Plants in the family Melianthaceae are rich sources of bufadienolides (S. Steyn and R. van Heerden, 1998), a group of compounds with a steroidal structure having a 17 β -2H-pyran-2-one ring system. Previous phytochemical studies on the plant led to identification of several cytotoxic bufadienolides (Kupchan et al., 1971a; Kupchan et al., 1971b;
).
Bersama abyssinica
has been used as a source of traditional medicine for various ailments (
; Kupchan et al., 1971a). The leaf decoctions are used to treat stomach disorders such as diarrhea, cholera, dysentery, and intestinal worms. Earlier pharmacological studies on different extracts of
Bersama
plant exhibited antimicrobial (
) and antitumor activities (Kupchan et al., 1971a; Kupchan et al., 1971b).

